We define some variables for [[w:well-formed formula|well-formed formula]]s:

Some of the proofs here are adapted, or even entirely copy-pasted, from pages such as [[Principia Mathematica propositional logic]] or [[Standard axioms imply Principia Mathematica axioms]]. It would be possible to reduce this duplication by having some of the other pages build on [[Interface:Intuitionistic propositional logic]], but the presentation might become less clear in other ways (certainly it would less closely track the way things are developed in ''Principia''), so we do not currently have the intuitionistic tail wag the classical dog.

Some proofs are taken from metamath's set.mm.  In particular, metamath's section "Logical implication" makes use only of the two axioms <code>Simp</code> and <code>Frege</code>, and thus is entirely valid in an intuitionistic context.<ref>[http://us.metamath.org/mpeuni/mmtheorems.html#mm2b Propositional calculus], from Metamath Proof Explorer, accessed February 26, 2010</ref>

== Implication ==

=== Rule for antecedent distribution ===

It will be convenient to have the ''Frege'' axiom as a rule:
* #(→ (→ p q) (→ p r))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/distributeAntecedent | distributeAntecedent])

=== Syllogism ===

Next we derive the syllogism, which allows us to combine several implications.
* #(→ p r)# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/applySyllogism | applySyllogism])

=== Implication reflexivity ===

Any proposition implies itself:
* #(→ p p)# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/Id | Id])
* #(→ p p)# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/ImplicationReflexivity | ImplicationReflexivity])

=== More common operations ===
Given a nested implication we often want to exchange the two antecedents:
* #(→ q (→ p r))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/applyComm | applyComm])

If we have an implication, adding a common term to the antecedent and the consequent yields a new theorem:
* #(→ (→ p q) (→ (→ r p) (→ r q)))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/CommonAntecedentAddition | CommonAntecedentAddition])
* #(→ (→ r p) (→ r q))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/addCommonAntecedent | addCommonAntecedent])

The analogous operation adding consequents swaps the initial antecedent and consequent:
* #(→ (→ p q) (→ (→ q r) (→ p r)))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/CommonConsequentAddition | CommonConsequentAddition])
* #(→ (→ q r) (→ p r))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/addCommonConsequent | addCommonConsequent])

Here's a theorem form of <code>applyComm</code>:
* #(→ (→ p (→ q r)) (→ q (→ p r)))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/Comm | Comm])

=== Absorb redundant antecedent ===

We can absorb a redundant antecedent:
* #(→ (→ p (→ p q)) (→ p q))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/RedundantAntecedentAbsorption | RedundantAntecedentAbsorption])
* #(→ p q)# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/absorbRedundantAntecedent | absorbRedundantAntecedent])

=== Antecedent introduction ===
We provide another name and a rule form for the <code>Simp</code> axiom:
* #(→ p (→ q p))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/AntecedentIntroduction | AntecedentIntroduction])
* #(→ q p)# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/introduceAntecedent | introduceAntecedent])

=== Converse of antecedent distribution ===
The converse of the <code>Frege</code> axiom also holds.<ref>[http://us.metamath.org/mpeuni/pm2.86.html pm2.86] in metamath's set.mm, accessed May 14, 2010</ref>
* #(→ (→ (→ p q) (→ p r)) (→ p (→ q r)))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/FregeConverse | FregeConverse])
* #(→ p (→ q r))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/collectAntecedent | collectAntecedent])

=== Syllogism in the consequent ===
This theorem is similar to syllogism, but where each piece has a common antecedent.
* #(→ (→ p (→ q r)) (→ (→ p (→ r s)) (→ p (→ q s))))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/SyllogismInConsequent | SyllogismInConsequent])
* #(→ p (→ q s))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/applySyllogismInConsequent | applySyllogismInConsequent])

== Conjunction ==

=== Rules ===
If we can prove two propositions, the conjunction of the two follows (this is just a rule form of the <code>ConjunctionRightIntroduction</code> axiom):
* #(∧ p q)# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/introduceConjunction | introduceConjunction])

Here are rules for the <code>ConjunctionLeftElimination</code> and <code>ConjunctionRightElimination</code> axioms:
* #('q')# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/eliminateLeftConjunct | eliminateLeftConjunct])
* #('p')# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/eliminateRightConjunct | eliminateRightConjunct])

=== Left introduction ===
Most of the introduction and elimination statements we need to provide are axioms, but this one is a simple consequence of the axioms:
* #(→ p (→ q (∧ q p)))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/ConjunctionLeftIntroduction | ConjunctionLeftIntroduction])

=== Conjunction composition ===
Our first major theorem relating conjunction to implication is composition: from <code>p → q</code> and <code>p → r</code>, we can conclude <code>p → (q ∧ r)</code>.
* #(→ (→ p q) (→ (→ p r) (→ p (∧ q r))))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/ConjunctionComposition1 | ConjunctionComposition1])
* #(→ p (∧ q r))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/composeConjunction | composeConjunction])

We also prove a version of the converse:
* #(→ (→ p (∧ q r)) (∧ (→ p q) (→ p r)))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/ConjunctionCompositionReverse | ConjunctionCompositionReverse])
* #(→ p q)# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/extractLeftConjunction | extractLeftConjunction])
* #(→ p r)# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/extractRightConjunction | extractRightConjunction])

=== Export and import ===
The import and export theorems from classical propositional logic also hold in intuitionistic logic. We start with export, <code>(p ∧ q → r) → (p → (q → r))</code>. The proof is based around a variant of CommonConsequentAddition which has two antecedents, rather than one.

* #(→ (→ p (→ q r)) (→ (→ r common) (→ p (→ q common))))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/CommonConsequentAdditionToNestedImplication | CommonConsequentAdditionToNestedImplication])
* #(→ (→ (∧ p q) r) (→ p (→ q r)))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/Exportation | Exportation])
* #(→ p (→ q r))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/export | export])

The proof of export was based around having a conjunction as a consequent, that is <code>p → (q → p ∧ q)</code>.  The proof of import is based around <code>p ∧ q → p</code> (and likewise for <code>q</code>). The following lemma is what we'll use to glue together the different parts of the proof, and is basically a gussied up variant of applySyllogism:

* #(→ P (→ Q r))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/ImportLemma | ImportLemma])
* #(→ (→ p (→ q r)) (→ (∧ p q) r))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/Importation | Importation])
* #(→ (∧ p q) r)# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/import | import])

=== Implication transitivity and other consequences of import ====
The form of the syllogism in [[Interface:Intuitionistic propositional logic]] is easy now that we have import:

* #(→ (∧ (→ p q) (→ q r)) (→ p r))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/ImplicationTransitivity | ImplicationTransitivity])

Likewise, we restate <code>ConjunctionComposition1</code> using the new tool:
* #(→ (∧ (→ p q) (→ p r)) (→ p (∧ q r)))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/ConjunctionCompositionForward | ConjunctionCompositionForward])

=== Commutativity ===
* #(→ (∧ p q) (∧ q p))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/ConjunctionCommutativityImplication | ConjunctionCommutativityImplication])
* #(∧ q p)# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/swapConjunction | swapConjunction])

=== Builders ===

==== ConjunctionMultiplicationRR ====

Our first major builder lets us add a common conjunct to both sides of an implication.  We start with a few lemmas, and then prove the main theorem.

* #(→ (→ p q) (→ (∧ p common) q))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/ConjunctionMultiplicationRX-q | ConjunctionMultiplicationRX-q])
* #(→ (→ p q) (→ (∧ p common) common))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/ConjunctionMultiplicationRX-common | ConjunctionMultiplicationRX-common])
* #(→ (→ p q) (→ (∧ p common) (∧ q common)))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/ConjunctionMultiplicationRR | ConjunctionMultiplicationRR])
* #(→ (∧ p r) (∧ q r))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/conjoinRR | conjoinRR])

==== Other builders ====
The rest of the <code>ConjunctionMultiplication</code> variants follow from the first one, just like in [[Principia Mathematica propositional logic]].

* #(→ (∧ (→ p r) (→ q s)) (→ (∧ p q) (∧ r s)))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/ConjunctionMultiplication | ConjunctionMultiplication])
* #(→ (∧ p q) (∧ r s))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/conjoin | conjoin])
* #(→ (→ p q) (→ (∧ r p) (∧ r q)))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/ConjunctionMultiplicationLL | ConjunctionMultiplicationLL])
* #(→ (→ p q) (→ (∧ r p) (∧ q r)))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/ConjunctionMultiplicationLR | ConjunctionMultiplicationLR])
* #(→ (→ p q) (→ (∧ p r) (∧ r q)))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/ConjunctionMultiplicationRL | ConjunctionMultiplicationRL])
* #(→ (∧ r p) (∧ r q))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/conjoinLL | conjoinLL])
* #(→ (∧ r p) (∧ q r))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/conjoinLR | conjoinLR])
* #(→ (∧ p r) (∧ r q))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/conjoinRL | conjoinRL])

== Disjunction ==
We provide a variation of the disjunction composition axiom, and a rule form:
* #(→ (→ (∨ p q) r) (∧ (→ p r) (→ q r)))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/DisjunctionCompositionReverse | DisjunctionCompositionReverse])
* #(→ (∨ p q) r)# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/composeDisjunction | composeDisjunction])

Here are a few other rules corresponding to axioms.
* #(∨ q p)# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/introduceLeftDisjunction | introduceLeftDisjunction])
* #(∨ p q)# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/introduceRightDisjunction | introduceRightDisjunction])
* #(→ p r)# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/extractLeftDisjunction | extractLeftDisjunction])
* #(→ q r)# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/extractRightDisjunction | extractRightDisjunction])

=== Commutativity ===
* #(→ (∨ p q) (∨ q p))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/DisjunctionCommutativityImplication | DisjunctionCommutativityImplication])
* #(∨ q p)# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/swapDisjunction | swapDisjunction])

=== Builders ===

==== DisjunctionSummationRL ====

Our first disjunction builder is proved analogously to <code>ConjunctionMultiplicationRR</code>.

* #(→ (→ p q) (→ p (∨ common q)))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/DisjunctionSummationXL-p | DisjunctionSummationXL-p])
* #(→ (→ p q) (→ common (∨ common q)))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/DisjunctionSummationXL-common | DisjunctionSummationXL-common])
* #(→ (→ p q) (→ (∨ p common) (∨ common q)))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/DisjunctionSummationRL | DisjunctionSummationRL])
* #(→ (∨ p r) (∨ r q))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/disjoinRL | disjoinRL])

==== DisjunctionSummation ====

This theorem follows exactly as <code>ConjunctionMultiplication</code>, except that we use <code>DisjunctionSummationRL</code> instead of <code>ConjunctionMultiplicationRR</code> and <code>ConjunctionCommutativity</code>.

* #(→ (∧ (→ p r) (→ q s)) (→ (∨ p q) (∨ r s)))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/DisjunctionSummation | DisjunctionSummation])
* #(→ (∨ p q) (∨ r s))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/disjoin | disjoin])

==== DisjunctionSummation variations ====
We could prove the <code>DisjunctionSummationLL</code>, <code>DisjunctionSummationRR</code>, and <code>DisjunctionSummationLR</code> the same way that we proved <code>DisjunctionSummationRL</code>, but here we prove them as special cases of <code>DisjunctionSummation</code>.

* #(→ (→ p q) (→ (∨ r p) (∨ r q)))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/DisjunctionSummationLL | DisjunctionSummationLL])
* #(→ (→ p q) (→ (∨ r p) (∨ q r)))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/DisjunctionSummationLR | DisjunctionSummationLR])
* #(→ (→ p q) (→ (∨ p r) (∨ q r)))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/DisjunctionSummationRR | DisjunctionSummationRR])
* #(→ (∨ r p) (∨ r q))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/disjoinLL | disjoinLL])
* #(→ (∨ r p) (∨ q r))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/disjoinLR | disjoinLR])
* #(→ (∨ p r) (∨ q r))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/disjoinRR | disjoinRR])

== Biconditional ==

We define the biconditional as the conjunction of two implications:

* #(∧ (→ (∧ (→ p q) (→ q p)) (∧ (→ p q) (→ q p))) (→ (∧ (→ p q) (→ q p)) (∧ (→ p q) (→ q p))))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/BiconditionalJust | BiconditionalJust])
* defthm Biconditional

And one way to prove a biconditional is to prove both of the implications:
* #(↔ p q)# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/introduceBiconditionalFromImplications | introduceBiconditionalFromImplications])

We can eliminate one of the implications of a biconditional:
* #(→ (↔ p q) (→ q p))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/BiconditionalForwardElimination | BiconditionalForwardElimination])
* #(→ (↔ p q) (→ p q))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/BiconditionalReverseElimination | BiconditionalReverseElimination])
* #(→ q p)# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/eliminateBiconditionalForward | eliminateBiconditionalForward])
* #(→ p q)# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/eliminateBiconditionalReverse | eliminateBiconditionalReverse])

=== Biconditionalized versions of some theorems we've already proved ===
We've proved both directions of each of the following theorems, so the biconditional immediately follows:
* #(↔ (→ p (→ q r)) (→ (→ p q) (→ p r)))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/AntecedentDistribution | AntecedentDistribution])
* #(↔ (→ p (→ q r)) (→ (∧ p q) r))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/Transportation | Transportation])
* #(↔ (∧ (→ p q) (→ p r)) (→ p (∧ q r)))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/ConjunctionComposition | ConjunctionComposition])
* #(↔ (∧ (→ p r) (→ q r)) (→ (∨ p q) r))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/DisjunctionComposition | DisjunctionComposition])

=== Reflexive, symmetric, and transitive ===

The biconditional has these three properties (which correspond to those defining an [[w:equivalence relation|equivalence relation]]). The proofs here are taken directly from [[Principia Mathematica propositional logic]], as they are also valid in intuitionistic logic.

* #(↔ p p)# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/BiconditionalReflexivity | BiconditionalReflexivity])
* #(→ (↔ p q) (↔ q p))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/BiconditionalSymmetryImplication | BiconditionalSymmetryImplication])
* #(↔ (↔ p q) (↔ q p))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/BiconditionalSymmetry | BiconditionalSymmetry])
* #(↔ q p)# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/swapBiconditional | swapBiconditional])
* #(→ (∧ (↔ p q) (↔ q r)) (↔ p r))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/BiconditionalTransitivity | BiconditionalTransitivity])
* #(↔ p r)# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/applyBiconditionalTransitivity | applyBiconditionalTransitivity])

=== Relating biconditional to implications ===

The following just restate the definition of the biconditional.
* #(↔ (↔ p q) (∧ (→ p q) (→ q p)))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/BiconditionalImplication | BiconditionalImplication])
* #(∧ (→ p q) (→ q p))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/convertFromBiconditionalToImplications | convertFromBiconditionalToImplications])
* #(↔ p q)# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/convertToBiconditionalFromImplications | convertToBiconditionalFromImplications])

=== Algebraic laws for disjunction and conjunction ===
Most of the theorems of the propositional calculus which are analagous to those of other [[w:Abstract algebra|algebras]], showing properties such as commutivity and associativity, also hold for intuitionistic logic.

==== Conjunction idempotence ====
* #(→ p (∧ p p))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/ConjunctionIdempotenceForward | ConjunctionIdempotenceForward])
* #(→ (∧ p p) p)# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/ConjunctionIdempotenceReverse | ConjunctionIdempotenceReverse])
* #(↔ p (∧ p p))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/ConjunctionIdempotence | ConjunctionIdempotence])
* #(∧ p p)# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/cloneAsConjunction | cloneAsConjunction])
* #('p')# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/conflateConjunction | conflateConjunction])

==== Conjunction commutativity ====
* #(↔ (∧ p q) (∧ q p))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/ConjunctionCommutativity | ConjunctionCommutativity])

==== Conjunction associativity ====
To prove associativity for conjunctions, <code>(p ∧ q) ∧ r → p ∧ (q ∧ r)</code>, we first put onto the proof stack the statements that the left hand side implies each of <code>p</code>, <code>q</code>, and <code>r</code>.
* #(→ (∧ (∧ p q) r) (∧ p (∧ q r)))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/ConjunctionRightAssociation | ConjunctionRightAssociation])

The proof for associating left is similar.
* #(→ (∧ p (∧ q r)) (∧ (∧ p q) r))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/ConjunctionLeftAssociation | ConjunctionLeftAssociation])
* #(↔ (∧ (∧ p q) r) (∧ p (∧ q r)))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/ConjunctionAssociativity | ConjunctionAssociativity])
* #(∧ p (∧ q r))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/groupConjunctionRight | groupConjunctionRight])
* #(∧ (∧ p q) r)# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/groupConjunctionLeft | groupConjunctionLeft])

==== Disjunction idempotence ====
* #(→ p (∨ p p))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/DisjunctionIdempotenceForward | DisjunctionIdempotenceForward])
* #(→ (∨ p p) p)# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/DisjunctionIdempotenceReverse | DisjunctionIdempotenceReverse])
* #(↔ p (∨ p p))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/DisjunctionIdempotence | DisjunctionIdempotence])
* #(∨ p p)# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/cloneAsDisjunction | cloneAsDisjunction])
* #('p')# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/conflateDisjunction | conflateDisjunction])

==== Disjunction commutativity ====
* #(↔ (∨ p q) (∨ q p))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/DisjunctionCommutativity | DisjunctionCommutativity])

==== Disjunction associativity ====
Proving associativity for disjunction is very much analogous to conjunction, with conjunction elimination and composition changed to disjunction introduction and composition.
* #(→ (∨ (∨ p q) r) (∨ p (∨ q r)))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/DisjunctionRightAssociation | DisjunctionRightAssociation])
* #(→ (∨ p (∨ q r)) (∨ (∨ p q) r))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/DisjunctionLeftAssociation | DisjunctionLeftAssociation])
* #(↔ (∨ (∨ p q) r) (∨ p (∨ q r)))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/DisjunctionAssociativity | DisjunctionAssociativity])
* #(∨ (∨ p q) r)# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/groupDisjunctionLeft | groupDisjunctionLeft])
* #(∨ p (∨ q r))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/groupDisjunctionRight | groupDisjunctionRight])

=== Builders ===

The builders for conjunction and disjunction can be proved using the proofs in [[Principia Mathematica propositional logic]].

==== Conjunction ====

* #(→ (∧ (∧ p q) (∧ r s)) (∧ (∧ p r) (∧ q s)))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/ConjunctionFunction-1 | ConjunctionFunction-1])
* #(→ (∧ (↔ p q) (↔ r s)) (↔ (∧ p r) (∧ q s)))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/ConjunctionFunction | ConjunctionFunction])
* #(↔ (∧ p r) (∧ q s))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/buildConjunction | buildConjunction])

==== Disjunction ====
This is just like the theorem for conjunction, except that we build on the partial builder theorem <code>DisjunctionSummation</code> instead of <code>ConjunctionMultiplication</code>:

* #(→ (∧ (↔ p q) (↔ r s)) (↔ (∨ p r) (∨ q s)))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/DisjunctionFunction | DisjunctionFunction])
* #(↔ (∨ p r) (∨ q s))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/buildDisjunction | buildDisjunction])

=== Distributivity ===
Here we take up distributivity of disjunction over conjunction, and conjunction over disjunction.  Most of the proofs given in [[Principia Mathematica propositional logic]] apply for intuitionistic logic, as they are fairly straightforward applications of disjunction and conjunction composition.  The tough one is <code>((p ∨ q) ∧ (p ∨ r)) → p ∨ (q ∧ r)</code> (because it has a conjunction in the antecedent and a disjunction in the consequent, it won't yield to straightforward composition tricks).  ''Principia'' proves it from the equivalence of <code>p ∨ q</code> and <code>¬ p → q</code> (which does not hold in both directions in intuitionistic logic).  We prove it from import and builders.

The first step is a lemma which will let us harmlessly apply builders more than once.
* #(→ (∨ p (∨ p q)) (∨ p q))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/RedundantDisjunctionAbsorption | RedundantDisjunctionAbsorption])

Now we are ready for the proof of the tough distributivity case.
* #(→ (∧ (∨ p q) (∨ p r)) (∨ p (∧ q r)))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/DisjunctionLeftDistribution-reverse | DisjunctionLeftDistribution-reverse])

The rest of this section contains proofs taken from [[Principia Mathematica propositional logic]].

* #(→ (∧ p (∨ q r)) (∨ (∧ p q) (∧ p r)))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/ConjunctionLeftDistribution-forward | ConjunctionLeftDistribution-forward])
* #(→ (∨ (∧ p q) (∧ p r)) (∧ p (∨ q r)))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/ConjunctionLeftDistribution-reverse | ConjunctionLeftDistribution-reverse])
* #(↔ (∧ p (∨ q r)) (∨ (∧ p q) (∧ p r)))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/ConjunctionLeftDistribution | ConjunctionLeftDistribution])
* #(→ (∨ p (∧ q r)) (∧ (∨ p q) (∨ p r)))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/DisjunctionLeftDistribution-forward | DisjunctionLeftDistribution-forward])
* #(↔ (∨ p (∧ q r)) (∧ (∨ p q) (∨ p r)))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/DisjunctionLeftDistribution | DisjunctionLeftDistribution])

Also from [[Principia Mathematica propositional logic]] are commuted versions of both laws and some rules:

* #(↔ (∨ (∧ p q) r) (∧ (∨ p r) (∨ q r)))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/DisjunctionRightDistribution | DisjunctionRightDistribution])
* #(↔ (∧ (∨ p q) r) (∨ (∧ p r) (∧ q r)))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/ConjunctionRightDistribution | ConjunctionRightDistribution])
* #(∧ (∨ p q) (∨ p r))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/distributeLeftDisjunction | distributeLeftDisjunction])
* #(∨ p (∧ q r))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/collectLeftDisjunction | collectLeftDisjunction])
* #(∧ (∨ p r) (∨ q r))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/distributeRightDisjunction | distributeRightDisjunction])
* #(∨ (∧ p q) r)# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/collectRightDisjunction | collectRightDisjunction])
* #(∨ (∧ p q) (∧ p r))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/distributeLeftConjunction | distributeLeftConjunction])
* #(∧ p (∨ q r))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/collectLeftConjunction | collectLeftConjunction])
* #(∨ (∧ p r) (∧ q r))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/distributeRightConjunction | distributeRightConjunction])
* #(∧ (∨ p q) r)# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/collectRightConjunction | collectRightConjunction])

=== Biconditional and conjunction ===
A true conjunct does not affect the truth of a proposition. The proof from [[Principia Mathematica propositional logic]] is valid intuitionistically without change.

* #(↔ (→ p q) (→ p (∧ p q)))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/*4.7 | *4.7])
* #(↔ (→ p q) (↔ p (∧ p q)))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/*4.71 | *4.71])
* #(→ q (↔ p (∧ p q)))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/BiconditionalConjunct | BiconditionalConjunct])

== Modus Ponens ==
This is just an implication corresponding to the modus ponens rule:
* #(→ (∧ p (→ p q)) q)# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/ModusPonens | ModusPonens])

== Negation ==

=== Transposition ===
Although intuitionistic logic does not allow removing transposition, it does allow introducing it.
* #(→ (→ p q) (→ (¬ q) (¬ p)))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/TranspositionIntroduction | TranspositionIntroduction])
* #(→ (¬ q) (¬ p))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/introduceTransposition | introduceTransposition])

Modus tollens is an easy consequence of transposition introduction.

* #(→ (∧ (¬ q) (→ p q)) (¬ p))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/ModusTollens | ModusTollens])
* #(¬ p)# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/applyModusTollens | applyModusTollens])

=== Double Negation ===
Double negation introduction follows fairly directly from our first negation axiom.
* #(→ p (¬ (¬ p)))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/DoubleNegationIntroduction | DoubleNegationIntroduction])
* #(¬ (¬ p))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/introduceDoubleNegation | introduceDoubleNegation])

=== Triple negation ===
In intuitionistic logic, <code>¬ ¬ p</code> is not equivalent to <code>p</code> itself. Triple negation, however, is equivalent to single negation, so one merely needs to worry about formulas without negation, with single negation, or with double negation, not greater amounts of negation.
* #(↔ (¬ (¬ (¬ p))) (¬ p))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/TripleNegation | TripleNegation])
* #(¬ p)# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/eliminateTripleNegation | eliminateTripleNegation])

=== Disjunctive syllogism ===
[[w:Disjunctive syllogism|Disjunctive syllogism]]:
* #(→ (→ p q) (→ (∨ p q) q))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/DisjunctiveSyllogismLemma | DisjunctiveSyllogismLemma])
* #(→ (∧ (¬ p) (∨ p q)) q)# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/DisjunctiveSyllogism | DisjunctiveSyllogism])

=== DeMorgan's laws ===

The first two of DeMorgan's laws are straightforward:
* #(→ (¬ (∨ p q)) (∧ (¬ p) (¬ q)))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/NegationDistributionPDP | NegationDistributionPDP])
* #(→ (∨ (¬ p) (¬ q)) (¬ (∧ p q)))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/NegationCollectionNDN | NegationCollectionNDN])

To prove the converse of <code>NegationDistributionPDP</code>, we start with a lemma which is a rearrangement of <code>DisjunctiveSyllogism</code> plus transposition.
* #(→ (¬ p) (→ (¬ q) (¬ (∨ p q))))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/NegationCollectionNCNLemma | NegationCollectionNCNLemma])

This lemma is, however, just an import away from the desired result.
* #(→ (∧ (¬ p) (¬ q)) (¬ (∨ p q)))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/NegationCollectionNCN | NegationCollectionNCN])

Combining the forward and reverse directions we get <code>NegationCollectionNCNDistributionPDP</code>:
* #(↔ (∧ (¬ p) (¬ q)) (¬ (∨ p q)))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/NegationCollectionNCNDistributionPDP | NegationCollectionNCNDistributionPDP])

The following result follows from double negation introduction and <code>NegationCollectionNCNDistributionPDP</code>.
* #(→ (∧ p q) (¬ (∨ (¬ p) (¬ q))))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/NegationCollectionPCP | NegationCollectionPCP])

We can pull the same trick for disjunction to get our final version of DeMorgan's law.
* #(→ (∨ p q) (¬ (∧ (¬ p) (¬ q))))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/NegationCollectionPDP | NegationCollectionPDP])

Rules:
* #(¬ (∨ (¬ p) (¬ q)))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/collectNegationPCP | collectNegationPCP])
* #(¬ (∧ (¬ p) (¬ q)))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/collectNegationPDP | collectNegationPDP])
* #(¬ (∧ p q))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/collectNegationNDN | collectNegationNDN])
* #(¬ (∨ p q))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/collectNegationNCN | collectNegationNCN])
* #(∧ (¬ p) (¬ q))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/distributeNegationPDP | distributeNegationPDP])

=== Double negation and connectives ===
The first two of these relationships between double negation and conjunction or disjunction are easy consequences of transposition.
* #(→ (¬ (¬ (∧ p q))) (∧ (¬ (¬ p)) (¬ (¬ q))))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/DoubleNegatedConjunctionReverse | DoubleNegatedConjunctionReverse])
* #(→ (∨ (¬ (¬ p)) (¬ (¬ q))) (¬ (¬ (∨ p q))))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/DoubleNegatedDisjunction | DoubleNegatedDisjunction])

The converse of <code>DoubleNegatedConjunctionReverse</code> we can prove via the following lemma which introduces double negation to all three formulas of a nested implication.
* #(→ (¬ (¬ p)) (→ (¬ (¬ q)) (¬ (¬ r))))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/addDoubleNegationImplicationImplication | addDoubleNegationImplicationImplication])
* #(→ (∧ (¬ (¬ p)) (¬ (¬ q))) (¬ (¬ (∧ p q))))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/DoubleNegatedConjunctionForward | DoubleNegatedConjunctionForward])
* #(↔ (∧ (¬ (¬ p)) (¬ (¬ q))) (¬ (¬ (∧ p q))))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/DoubleNegatedConjunction | DoubleNegatedConjunction])

=== No contradictions ===
The <code>Explosion</code> axiom amounts to denying that a proposition and its negation can both hold. Here we express this idea as a theorem (which is also found as *3.24 in [[Principia Mathematica propositional logic]]).
* #(¬ (∧ p (¬ p)))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/NoContradiction | NoContradiction])

== Case elimination ==
Proving a theorem by cases, as in <code>CaseElimination</code> of [[Interface:Classical propositional calculus]], is not, in general, allowed in intuitionism/constructivism. For example, there is a well-known non-constructive proof that an irrational number raised to an irrational power can be rational that proceeds by handling the cases where √2<sup>√2</sup> is rational or irrational, without establishing which one holds. A constructive proof, on the other hand, would need to establish whether √2<sup>√2</sup> was rational first.<ref>Su, Francis E., et al. "[http://www.math.hmc.edu/funfacts/ffiles/10004.3-5.shtml Rational Irrational Power]," [http://www.math.hmc.edu/funfacts Mudd Math Fun Facts], accessed 3 Jul 2010</ref>  We do note that <code>p ∨ q</code>, which is stronger than <code>¬ p → q</code> in intuitionistic logic, can be used for case elimination. This is more of a curiosity than a way of proving anything, as proving <code>p ∨ q</code> in intuitionistic logic would tend to be as hard as proving <code>q</code>.
* #(→ (∧ (∨ p q) (∨ (¬ p) q)) q)# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/DisjunctiveCaseElimination | DisjunctiveCaseElimination])

== More builders ==
Now that we've proved some results involving negation, we are ready to tackle the rest of the builders.

=== Negation ===
The negation builder is an easy consequence of transposition introduction (we just need to biconditionalize it).
* #(→ (↔ p q) (↔ (¬ p) (¬ q)))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/NegationBuilder | NegationBuilder])
* #(↔ (¬ p) (¬ q))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/addNegation | addNegation])

=== Implication ===
The proof of the implication builder is analogous to the way we proved <code>ConjunctionMultiplication</code>. We base it on <code>CommonConsequentAddition</code> and <code>CommonAntecedentAddition</code>.

* #(→ (∧ (↔ p q) (↔ r s)) (→ (→ p r) (→ q r)))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/ImplicationFunction-1 | ImplicationFunction-1])
* #(→ (∧ (↔ p q) (↔ r s)) (→ (→ q r) (→ q s)))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/ImplicationFunction-2 | ImplicationFunction-2])
* #(→ (∧ (↔ p q) (↔ r s)) (→ (→ p r) (→ q s)))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/ImplicationFunction-3 | ImplicationFunction-3])
* #(→ (∧ (↔ p q) (↔ r s)) (↔ (→ p r) (→ q s)))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/ImplicationFunction | ImplicationFunction])
* #(↔ (→ p r) (→ q s))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/buildImplication | buildImplication])

=== Biconditional ===
We derive the biconditional builder from the implication builder, just as in [[Principia Mathematica propositional logic]].
* #(→ (∧ (↔ p q) (↔ r s)) (↔ (↔ p r) (↔ q s)))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/BiconditionalFunction | BiconditionalFunction])
* #(↔ (↔ p r) (↔ q s))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/buildBiconditional | buildBiconditional])

== Distribution of implication over biconditional ==

The proof of this result from [[Principia Mathematica propositional logic]] applies verbatim.
* #(↔ (→ p (↔ q r)) (↔ (→ p q) (→ p r)))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/ImplicationDistributionOverBiconditional | ImplicationDistributionOverBiconditional])
* #(↔ (→ p q) (→ p r))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/distributeImplicationOverBiconditional | distributeImplicationOverBiconditional])

== Relationships between connectives ==

=== Conjunction and implication ===
Analogous to DeMorgan's law, there are four relationships between conjunction and implication, which differ depending on where the negations are placed. They are:
 p ∧ q → ¬ (p → ¬ q)
 (p → q) → ¬ (p ∧ ¬ q)
 p ∧ ¬ q → ¬ (p → q)
 p → ¬ q ↔ ¬ (p ∧ q)

For now, we only prove the third one.

* #(→ (∧ p (¬ q)) (¬ (→ p q)))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/ConjunctionImplication3 | ConjunctionImplication3])

=== Disjunction and implication ===
* #(→ (∨ p q) (→ (¬ p) q))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/DisjunctionImplicationForward | DisjunctionImplicationForward])
* #(→ (¬ p) q)# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/convertFromDisjunctionToImplication | convertFromDisjunctionToImplication])

The following implication/disjunction theorems are easy consequences of this one.
* #(→ (∨ (¬ p) q) (→ p q))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/ImplicationDisjunctionReverse | ImplicationDisjunctionReverse])
* #(→ p q)# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/convertToImplicationFromDisjunction | convertToImplicationFromDisjunction])
* #(→ (¬ (→ p q)) (¬ (∨ (¬ p) q)))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/NotImplicationDisjunction | NotImplicationDisjunction])
* #(→ (¬ (→ (¬ p) q)) (¬ (∨ p q)))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/NotDisjunctionImplicationReverse | NotDisjunctionImplicationReverse])

The converse of <code>NotDisjunctionImplicationReverse</code> also holds, but is a bit more difficult. 

* #(→ (¬ (∨ p q)) (¬ (→ (¬ p) q)))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/NotDisjunctionImplicationForward | NotDisjunctionImplicationForward])
* #(↔ (¬ (∨ p q)) (¬ (→ (¬ p) q)))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/NotDisjunctionImplication | NotDisjunctionImplication])

=== Proving a biconditional from two disjunctions ===

Since a suitably negated disjunction implies an implication, the antecedent of this theorem readily reduces to <code>p → q</code> and <code>q → p</code>, which is what we need to prove <code>p ↔ q</code>.
* #(→ (∧ (∨ (¬ p) q) (∨ p (¬ q))) (↔ p q))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/BiconditionalConjunctionReverse | BiconditionalConjunctionReverse])
* #(↔ p q)# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/convertToBiconditionalFromConjunction | convertToBiconditionalFromConjunction])
* #(↔ p q)# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/introduceBiconditionalFromDisjunctions | introduceBiconditionalFromDisjunctions])

== True and false connectives ==
We already defined true (⊤) in [Axioms of intuitionistic propositional logic]. We define false (⊥) as ¬ ⊤.

* #(→ (∧ p q) (→ p q))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/*3.4 | *3.4])
* #(↔ (⊤) (¬ (∧ p (¬ p))))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/Truth | Truth])
* #(→ (∧ p q) (↔ p q))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/TruthBiconditional | TruthBiconditional])
* #(↔ (→ p p) (⊤))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/TautologyId | TautologyId])
* #(¬ (⊥))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/NotFalse | NotFalse])

The <code>Contradiction</code> theorem also holds.  To prove it the same way as <code>TautologyId</code> would require <code>¬ p ∧ ¬ q → (p ↔ q)</code> (*5.21 in [[Principia Mathematica propositional logic]]). We don't have that, but <code>Contradiction</code> follows without too much trouble from <code>Explosion</code>.
* #(→ (∧ p (¬ p)) (⊥))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/ContradictionForward | ContradictionForward])
* #(→ (⊥) (∧ p (¬ p)))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/ContradictionReverse | ContradictionReverse])
* #(↔ (∧ p (¬ p)) (⊥))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/Contradiction | Contradiction])

=== Negation and ⊥ ===

Here we show that <code>¬ p</code> is equivalent to <code>p → ⊥</code>.  In some axiomizations of intuitionistic logic, this is the definition of negation.  For us, it is a theorem.

* #(→ (¬ p) (→ p (⊥)))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/NegationImplicationForward | NegationImplicationForward])
* #(→ (→ p (⊥)) (¬ p))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/NegationImplicationReverse | NegationImplicationReverse])
* #(↔ (¬ p) (→ p (⊥)))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/NegationImplication | NegationImplication])
* #(→ p (⊥))# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/convertFromNegationToImplication | convertFromNegationToImplication])
* #(¬ p)# ([/general/Intuitionistic_propositional_logic.gh/convertToNegationFromImplication | convertToNegationFromImplication])

== Export ==
We have proved everything in [[Interface:Basic intuitionistic propositional logic]]. There are additional theorems in [[Interface:Intuitionistic propositional logic]], but those are proved in [[Convenience theorems of intuitionistic propositional logic]].

